Date: Wed, 27 Sep 2000 12:52:52 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Khaleej Times,Wed 27 Sep 2000 05:52:52 -0700 [edited

Fumigation of 'fever' area planes ordered
-----------------------------------------
UNITED ARAB EMIRATES: The UAE authorities yesterday said all flights coming
from areas infected with Rift Valley Fever will be fumigated at UAE
airports. The authorities also recommended strict inspections of all
imported animal feeds to ensure they are free of the virus [presumably
originating from virus-free areas?. It was also decided to ban livestock
imports from Djibouti. A spray campaign against mosquitoes will be launched
throughout he country, particularly in border areas and at entry points.
International health experts, meanwhile, surveyed border areas in Saudi
Arabia and Yemen yesterday to help arrest the spread of the fever. Officials
in both countries said the death toll rose by Monday night to 60 from 55.
Saudi Arabia said 148 people have been infected since the outbreak of the
disease, of whom 30 have died and 21 have recovered. Yemen said 113 people
were infected of whom 30 died. The Rome-based UN Food and Agriculture
Organisation (FAO) said on Monday it had reports of at least 74 deaths while
newspapers and local medical sources say more than 200 people have died.
An Omani delegation yesterday toured the most affected areas in Al Hudaidah
province in Yemen to study the situation.
