Date: Thu, 28 Sep 2000 13:15:15 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Yahoo Asia News, Thu 28 Sep 2000 2:51 PM SGT [edited

Singapore Ministry of Health Advises Against Travelling To Saudi Arabia and
Yemen
------------------------------------
SINGAPORE: In view of the outbreak of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) in Saudi
Arabia and Yemen, Singaporeans are advised to avoid travelling to these
countries. Rift Valley Fever (RVF) is a viral disease that affects cattle,
buffalo, sheep, goats, camels and humans. The incubation period of RVF in
humans varies from 2 to 6 days, but those who experience influenza-like
illness, with sudden onset of fever, headache, muscle pain and backache, are
advised to consult a doctor. Some patients may also experience neck
stiffness, discomfort when looking at bright light, drowsiness and vomiting.
Patients usually recover within 2 days to one week after the onset of the
illness. However, in some patients the illness can progress to haemorrhagic
fever, encephalitis , or infection of the eye. About one percent of humans
that become infected with RVF die of the disease. There is no known
effective medication or vaccine available [for humans.
